<span class="displaytext"><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s tax-free savings plan for new hampshire families:</u> </b> <p><b>today, governor (candidate full) outlined his middle class tax savings plan.</b> governor (candidate last)'s plan will allow the middle class in new hampshire to save tax-free by changing the tax rate on interest, capital gains and dividends to absolutely 0%. by helping more granite staters save and invest, we can meet the challenges of an aging population and ensure the financial security of america. </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last)'s plan will allow over 95% of american families to save and invest tax-free.</b> any taxpayer with adjusted gross income of under $200,000 would pay a tax rate of absolutely 0% on all of the income they earn from their savings, capital gains and dividends. </p><p><b>governor (candidate last)'s plan will help thousands of new hampshire taxpayers save and invest tax free.</b> based on 2005 tax returns: </p><p><b>- 303,367 new hampshire taxpayers who earned interest could have benefited from this tax break. <br/> - 165,777 new hampshire taxpayers who earned dividends could have benefited from this tax break. <br/> - 132,934 new hampshire taxpayers who earned capital gains could have benefited from this tax break.</b> </p><p><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s plan will help americans build wealth and become homeowners:</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate last)'s plan will help families save for new homes.</b> recent housing market difficulties offer an important reason for helping more people save and invest. as the market softens, credit has tightened. therefore lending standards will become much tougher. as exotic loans become less widespread, the traditional practice of saving for a home down-payment will be the new standard. governor (candidate last)'s plan will help granite staters save for down-payments and achieve the american dream of home ownership. </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last)'s plan will put more money in the hands of existing homeowners.</b> by providing taxpayers with a 0% tax rate on savings, the plan will help homeowners meet their current mortgage payments. this tax cut will put more money into the hands of new hampshire homeowners. </p><p><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s plan builds upon and extends pro-growth tax policies:</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate last)'s plan builds on pro-growth tax policies initiated in 2003.</b> in 2003, the united states passed major cuts in the tax rate on capital gains and dividends, instituting a new, lower top rate of 15%. these tax cuts galvanized our economy. granite staters were able to keep more of their capital gains and reinvest in the economy: </p><p><b>- the rate of growth in our economy more than tripled, going from 0.8% in the two years before the rate cuts to 3.1% in the two years following the tax cuts. </b></p><p>- following the capital gains tax rate cut in 2003, capital gains tax receipts actually increased from $58 billion in 2002 to $103 billion in 2006. </p><p><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s pro-growth tax agenda:</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate last) has proposed a strong tax relief agenda to strengthen new hampshire families.</b> governor (candidate last) will make the bush tax relief permanent, cut tax rates for all new hampshire residents, abolish the death tax, and make the corporate tax rate more competitive with the rest of the world. </p><p><b>- <a href="http://www.(candidate full).com/news/press-releases/abolishing_the_death_tax">click here</a> to read governor (candidate last)'s plan to cut taxes.</b> </p><p><b>by making the bush tax relief permanent, governor (candidate last) will preserve tax relief for hundreds of thousands of middle-class families in new hampshire: </b></p><p>- 539,000 total new hampshire taxpayers benefited from the tax relief in 2006. <br/> - 495,000 new hampshire taxpayers benefited from the rate reduction in the lowest tax bracket in 2006. <br/> - 186,000 new hampshire couples saw a reduction in the marriage penalty in 2006. <br/> - 130,000 new hampshire taxpayers benefited from the increased child credit in 2006.</p></span>



